# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dynamic-tree-structure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In computer science, a **disjoint-set data structure**, also called a **union–find data structure** or **merge–find set**, is a data structure that stores a collection of disjoint (non-overlapping) sets.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Equivalently, it stores a partition of a set into disjoint subsets.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] It provides operations for adding new sets, merging sets (replacing them with their union), and finding a representative member of a set.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The last operation makes it possible to determine efficiently whether any two elements belong to the same set or to different sets.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] While there are several ways of implementing disjoint-set data structures, in practice they are often identified with a particular implementation known as a **disjoint-set forest**.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This specialized type of forest performs union and find operations in near-constant amortized time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] For a sequence of m addition, union, or find operations on a disjoint-set forest with n nodes, the total time required is *O*(*m*α(*n*)), where α(*n*) is the extremely slow-growing inverse Ackermann function.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Although disjoint-set forests do not guarantee this time per operation, each operation rebalances the structure (via tree compression) so that subsequent operations become faster.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] As a result, disjoint-set forests are both asymptotically optimal and practically efficient.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures play a key role in Kruskal's algorithm for finding the minimum spanning tree of a graph.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The importance of minimum spanning trees means that disjoint-set data structures support a wide variety of algorithms.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In addition, these data structures find applications in symbolic computation and in compilers, especially for register allocation problems.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set forests were first described by Bernard A.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1973, their time complexity was bounded to $O(\log ^{*}(n))$ , the iterated logarithm of n , by Hopcroft and Ullman.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1975, Robert Tarjan was the first to prove the $O(m\alpha (n))$ (inverse Ackermann function) upper bound on the algorithm's time complexity.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1979, he showed that this was the lower bound for a certain class of algorithms, pointer algorithms, that include the Galler-Fischer structure.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1989, Fredman and Saks showed that $\Omega (\alpha (n))$ (amortized) words of $O(\log n)$ bits must be accessed by *any* disjoint-set data structure per operation, thereby proving the optimality of the data structure in this model.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1991, Galil and Italiano published a survey of data structures for disjoint-sets.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Anderson and Heather Woll described a parallelized version of Union–Find that never needs to block.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 2007, Sylvain Conchon and Jean-Christophe Filliâtre developed a semi-persistent version of the disjoint-set forest data structure and formalized its correctness using the proof assistant Rocq (then: *Coq*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] "Semi-persistent" means that previous versions of the structure are efficiently retained, but accessing previous versions of the data structure invalidates later ones.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Their fastest implementation achieves performance almost as efficient as the non-persistent algorithm.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] They do not perform a complexity analysis.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Variants of disjoint-set data structures with better performance on a restricted class of problems have also been considered.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Gabow and Tarjan showed that if the possible unions are restricted in certain ways, then a truly linear time algorithm is possible.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In particular, linear time is achievable if a "union tree" is given a priori.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is a tree that includes all elements of the sets.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Let p[*v*] denote the parent in the tree, then the assumption is that union operations must have the form **union**(*v*,p[*v*]) for some *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this and the following section we describe the most common implementation of the disjoint-set data structure, as a forest of parent pointer trees.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This representation is known as **Galler-Fischer trees**.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Each node in a disjoint-set forest consists of a pointer and some auxiliary information, either a size or a rank (but not both).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The pointers are used to make parent pointer trees, where each node that is not the root of a tree points to its parent.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] To distinguish root nodes from others, their parent pointers have invalid values, such as a circular reference to the node or a sentinel value.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Each tree represents a set stored in the forest, with the members of the set being the nodes in the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Root nodes provide set representatives: Two nodes are in the same set if and only if the roots of the trees containing the nodes are equal.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Nodes in the forest can be stored in any way convenient to the application, but a common technique is to store them in an array.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this case, parents can be indicated by their array index.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Every array entry requires Θ(log *n*) bits of storage for the parent pointer.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] A comparable or lesser amount of storage is required for the rest of the entry, so the number of bits required to store the forest is Θ(*n* log *n*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] If an implementation uses fixed size nodes (thereby limiting the maximum size of the forest that can be stored), then the necessary storage is linear in n.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures support three operations: Making a new set containing a new element; Finding the representative of the set containing a given element; and Merging two sets.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The `MakeSet` operation adds a new element into a new set containing only the new element, and the new set is added to the data structure.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the data structure is instead viewed as a partition of a set, then the `MakeSet` operation enlarges the set by adding the new element, and it extends the existing partition by putting the new element into a new subset containing only the new element.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In a disjoint-set forest, `MakeSet` initializes the node's parent pointer and the node's size or rank.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This operation has linear time complexity.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In particular, initializing a disjoint-set forest with n nodes requires *O*(*n*) time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lack of a parent assigned to the node implies that the node is not present in the forest.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In practice, `MakeSet` must be preceded by an operation that allocates memory to hold x.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] As long as memory allocation is an amortized constant-time operation, as it is for a good dynamic array implementation, it does not change the asymptotic performance of the random-set forest.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The `Find` operation follows the chain of parent pointers from a specified query node x until it reaches a root element.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This root element represents the set to which x belongs and may be x itself.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] `Find` returns the root element it reaches.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Performing a `Find` operation presents an important opportunity for improving the forest.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The time in a `Find` operation is spent chasing parent pointers, so a flatter tree leads to faster `Find` operations.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] When a `Find` is executed, there is no faster way to reach the root than by following each parent pointer in succession.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] However, the parent pointers visited during this search can be updated to point closer to the root.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Because every element visited on the way to a root is part of the same set, this does not change the sets stored in the forest.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] But it makes future `Find` operations faster, not only for the nodes between the query node and the root, but also for their descendants.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This updating is an important part of the disjoint-set forest's amortized performance guarantee.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] There are several algorithms for `Find` that achieve the asymptotically optimal time complexity.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] One family of algorithms, known as **path compression**, makes every node between the query node and the root point to the root.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This implementation makes two passes, one up the tree and one back down.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] It requires enough scratch memory to store the path from the query node to the root (in the above pseudocode, the path is implicitly represented using the call stack).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This can be decreased to a constant amount of memory by performing both passes in the same direction.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Tarjan and Van Leeuwen also developed one-pass `Find` algorithms that retain the same worst-case complexity but are more efficient in practice.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] These are called path splitting and path halving.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both of these update the parent pointers of nodes on the path between the query node and the root.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The operation `Union(*x*, *y*)` replaces the set containing x and the set containing y with their union.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] `Union` first uses `Find` to determine the roots of the trees containing x and y.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the roots are the same, there is nothing more to do.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Otherwise, the two trees must be merged.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is done by either setting the parent pointer of x's root to y's, or setting the parent pointer of y's root to x's.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The choice of which node becomes the parent has consequences for the complexity of future operations on the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] If it is done carelessly, trees can become excessively tall.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] For example, suppose that `Union` always made the tree containing x a subtree of the tree containing y.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The resulting forest contains a single tree whose root is n, and the path from 1 to n passes through every node in the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] For this forest, the time to run `Find(1)` is *O*(*n*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In an efficient implementation, tree height is controlled using **union by size** or **union by rank**.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both of these require a node to store information besides just its parent pointer.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This information is used to decide which root becomes the new parent.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both strategies ensure that trees do not become too deep.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In the case of union by size, a node stores its size, which is simply its number of descendants (including the node itself).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] When the trees with roots x and y are merged, the node with more descendants becomes the parent.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the two nodes have the same number of descendants, then either one can become the parent.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In both cases, the size of the new parent node is set to its new total number of descendants.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The number of bits necessary to store the size is clearly the number of bits necessary to store n.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This adds a constant factor to the forest's required storage.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] For union by rank, a node stores its *rank*, which is an upper bound for its height.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] When a node is initialized, its rank is set to zero.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] To merge trees with roots x and y, first compare their ranks.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the ranks are different, then the larger rank tree becomes the parent, and the ranks of x and y do not change.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the ranks are the same, then either one can become the parent, but the new parent's rank is incremented by one.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] While the rank of a node is clearly related to its height, storing ranks is more efficient than storing heights.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The height of a node can change during a `Find` operation, so storing ranks avoids the extra effort of keeping the height correct.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] It can be shown that every node has rank $\lfloor \log n\rfloor$ or less.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Consequently, each rank can be stored in *O*(log log *n*) bits and all the ranks can be stored in *O*(*n* log log *n*) bits.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes the ranks an asymptotically negligible portion of the forest's size.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is clear from the above implementations that the size and rank of a node do not matter unless a node is the root of a tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Once a node becomes a child, its size and rank are never accessed again.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] There is a variant of the `Union` operation in which the user determines the representative of the formed set.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is not hard to add this functionality to the above algorithms without losing efficiency.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] A disjoint-set forest implementation in which `Find` does not update parent pointers, and in which `Union` does not attempt to control tree heights, can have trees with height *O*(*n*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In such a situation, the `Find` and `Union` operations require *O*(*n*) time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] If an implementation uses path compression alone, then a sequence of n `MakeSet` operations, followed by up to *n* − 1 `Union` operations and *f* `Find` operations, has a worst-case running time of $\Theta (n+f\cdot \left(1+\log _{2+f/n}n\right))$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Using union by rank, but without updating parent pointers during `Find`, gives a running time of $\Theta (m\log n)$ for m operations of any type, up to n of which are `MakeSet` operations.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The combination of path compression, splitting, or halving, with union by size or by rank, reduces the running time for m operations of any type, up to n of which are `MakeSet` operations, to $\Theta (m\alpha (n))$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes the amortized running time of each operation $\Theta (\alpha (n))$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is asymptotically optimal, meaning that every disjoint set data structure must use $\Omega (\alpha (n))$ amortized time per operation.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Here, the function $\alpha (n)$ is the inverse Ackermann function.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The inverse Ackermann function grows extraordinarily slowly, so this factor is 4 or less for any n that can actually be written in the physical universe.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes disjoint-set operations practically amortized constant time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The precise analysis of the performance of a disjoint-set forest is somewhat intricate.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] However, there is a much simpler analysis that proves that the amortized time for any m `Find` or `Union` operations on a disjoint-set forest containing n objects is *O*(*m* log* *n*), where log* denotes the iterated logarithm.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lemma 1: As the find function follows the path along to the root, the rank of node it encounters is increasing.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] We claim that as Find and Union operations are applied to the data set, this fact remains true over time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Initially when each node is the root of its own tree, it's trivially true.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The only case when the rank of a node might be changed is when the Union by Rank operation is applied.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this case, a tree with smaller rank will be attached to a tree with greater rank, rather than vice versa.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] And during the find operation, all nodes visited along the path will be attached to the root, which has larger rank than its children, so this operation won't change this fact either.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lemma 2: A node u which is root of a subtree with rank r has at least $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Assume that a node u with rank r has at least 2*r* nodes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Then when two trees with rank r are merged using the operation Union by Rank, a tree with rank *r* + 1 results, the root of which has at least $2^{r}+2^{r}=2^{r+1}$ nodes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] From lemma 2, we know that a node u which is root of a subtree with rank r has at least $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] We will get the maximum number of nodes of rank r when each node with rank r is the root of a tree that has exactly $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] At any particular point in the execution, we can group the vertices of the graph into "buckets", according to their rank.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] We define the buckets' ranges inductively, as follows: Bucket 0 contains vertices of rank 0.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Bucket 2 contains vertices of ranks 2 and 3.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Then bucket B will have vertices with ranks in the interval $[{\text{tower}}(B-1),{\text{tower}}(B)-1]$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] We can make two observations about the buckets' sizes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The maximum number of elements in bucket $\left[B,2^{B}-1\right]$ is at most ${\frac {2n}{2^{B}}}$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Since each find operation makes exactly one traversal that leads to a root, we have *T*1 = *O*(*m*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Also, from the bound above on the number of buckets, we have *T*2 = *O*(*m*log**n*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] For T3, suppose we are traversing an edge from u to v, where u and v have rank in the bucket [*B*, 2*B* − 1] and v is not the root (at the time of this traversing, otherwise the traversal would be accounted for in T1).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Fix u and consider the sequence $v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{k}$ that take the role of v in different find operations.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Because of path compression and not accounting for the edge to a root, this sequence contains only different nodes and because of Lemma 1 we know that the ranks of the nodes in this sequence are strictly increasing.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The worst-case time of the `Find` operation in trees with **Union by rank** or **Union by weight** is $\Theta (\log n)$ (i.e., it is $O(\log n)$ and this bound is tight).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Blum gave an implementation of the operations that does not use path compression, but compresses trees during $union$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] His implementation runs in $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ time per operation, and thus in comparison with Galler and Fischer's structure it has a better worst-case time per operation, but inferior amortized time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1999, Alstrup et al. gave a structure that has optimal worst-case time $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ together with inverse-Ackermann amortized time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The regular implementation as disjoint-set forests does not react favorably to the deletion of elements, in the sense that the time for `Find` will not improve as a result of the decrease in the number of elements.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is possible to extend certain disjoint-set forest structures to allow backtracking.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The basic form of backtracking is to allow a `Backtrack(1)` operation, that undoes the last `Union`.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] A more advanced form allows `Backtrack(i)`, which undoes the last i unions.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The following complexity result is known: there is a data structure which supports `Union` and `Find` in $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ time per operation, and `Backtrack` in $O(1)$ time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this result, the freedom of `Union` to choose the representative of the formed set is essential.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Better amortized time cannot be achieved within the class of separable pointer algorithms.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures model the partitioning of a set, for example to keep track of the connected components of an undirected graph.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This model can then be used to determine whether two vertices belong to the same component, or whether adding an edge between them would result in a cycle.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The Union–Find algorithm is used in high-performance implementations of unification.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] This data structure is used by the Boost Graph Library to implement its Incremental Connected Components functionality.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is also a key component in implementing Kruskal's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a graph.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] The Hoshen-Kopelman algorithm uses a Union-Find.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/disjoint-set-data-structure] Union-find can be used to implement reasonably performant Type inference algorithms.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] In computing and graph theory, a **dynamic connectivity** structure is a data structure that dynamically maintains information about the connected components of a graph.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The set *V* of vertices of the graph is fixed, but the set *E* of edges can change.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] After each addition/deletion of an edge, the dynamic connectivity structure should adapt itself such that it can give quick answers to queries of the form "is there a path between *x* and *y*?" (equivalently: "do vertices *x* and *y* belong to the same connected component?").
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If edges can only be added, then the dynamic connectivity problem can be solved by a disjoint-set data structure.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Each set represents a connected component; there is a path between *x* and *y* if and only if they belong to the same set.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The amortized time per operation is $\Theta (\alpha (n))$ , where *n* is the number of vertices and α is the inverse Ackermann function.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The case in which edges can only be deleted was solved by Shimon Even and Yossi Shiloach.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The structure uses a *table* that specifies, for each vertex, the name of the component to which it belongs.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Thus a connectivity query takes constant time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The challenge is to update the table when an edge is deleted.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] When edge *u*-*v* is deleted in a forest, the tree containing that edge is broken to two trees: one of them contains *u* and the other contains *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The table is updated in the following way.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Since we always rename the smaller sub-component, the amortized time for a delete operation is $O(\log(n))$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] When an edge is deleted in a general graph, we don't know whether its component remains a single component (connected by other edges) or broken to two components.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] So we use two processes which run in parallel (or in an interleaved way).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Process A checks whether the edge deletion breaks a component, and if it does, both processes halt.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Process B checks whether the edge deletion does not break the component to which it belongs, and if it does not, again both processes halt.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] is similar to the acyclic-graph case: there are two sub-processes who scan from both ends of the deleted edge.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If one of the sub-processes finishes before reaching the other end, this means that the component is broken into two sub-components, and the name of the smaller sub-component is updated, as before.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Artificial edges are introduced in order to keep all the connected components in one BFS structure and are used only for this purpose.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Clearly, the artificial edges are used only in process B.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The structure has the following properties.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] So for each vertex *v*, we maintain three sets of edges (backward, local and forward).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] When an edge *u*-*v* is deleted, there are two options: either *u* and *v* are in the same level, or they are in levels whose number differs by 1.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] In this case, the edge deletion cannot change the components.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] , and process B halts (and therefore process A is halted too).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Process B halts (and process A is halted too).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] , whose distance from the root increases as a result of the deletion.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Remove *w* from its level (say, *j*), and put it in the next level (*j*+1).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If the new backward(*w*) is empty, enqueue *w* again on Q.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If the edge deletion does not break any component and we are in case 2.2, then eventually the procedure will halt.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] In this case it is easy to see that the BFS structure is maintained correctly.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If its deletion does break a component, then the procedure will not halt by itself.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] However, process A, recognizing the break, will halt, and both processes will halt.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] In this case all the changes made in the BFS structure are ignored, and we go back to the BFS structure we had just before the deletion, except that the deleted edge is now replaced by an artificial edge.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Clearly, in this case *v* is now the root of a tree which includes the new component, and perhaps additional components, through some other artificial edges.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Also, there are no edges connecting the descendants of v with any vertices which are not v's descendants, except the artificial edge ⁠ $u-v$ ⁠.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] whenever an edge is processed in the procedure, one of its endpoints drops by one level.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Since the lowest level a vertex can reach in runs which are terminated by process B is $|V|-1$ , the cost per edge is bounded by $2|V|$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Hence the amortized time per deletion operation is $O(n)$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] A forest can be represented using a collection of either link-cut trees or Euler tour trees.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Then the dynamic connectivity problem can be solved easily, as for every two nodes x,y, x is connected to y if and only if $\mathrm {FindRoot} (x)=\mathrm {FindRoot} (y)$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The amortized update time and query time are both O(log(*n*)).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] A general graph can be represented by its spanning forest - a forest which contains a tree for every connected component of the graph.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] *F* itself can be represented by a forest of Euler tour trees.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The Query and Insert operations are implemented using the corresponding operations on the ET trees representing *F*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The challenging operation is Delete, and in particular, deleting an edge which is contained in one of the spanning trees of *F*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] This breaks the spanning tree into two trees, but, it is possible that there is another edge which connects them.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The challenge is to quickly find such a replacement edge, if it exists.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] This requires a more complex data structure.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Several such structures are described below.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Each edge in the graph is assigned a *level*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The level of each edge inserted to the graph is initialized to *L*, and may decrease towards 0 during delete operations.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] For each *i* between 0 and *L*, define *Gi* as the subgraph consisting of edges that are at level *i* or less, and *Fi* a spanning forest of *Gi*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Our forest *F* from before is now called *FL*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] We will keep a decreasing sequence of forests *FL* ⊇ ... ⊇ *F*0.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The Query and Insert operations use only the largest forest *FL*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The smaller subgraphs are consulted only during a Delete operation, and in particular, deleting an edge which is contained in one of the spanning trees of *FL*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] When such an edge *e* = *x*−*y* is deleted, it is first removed from *FL* and from all smaller spanning forests to which it belongs, i.e. from every *Fi* with *i* ≥ level(*e*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Start with the smallest spanning forest which contained *e*, namely, *Fi* with *i* = level(*e*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The edge *e* belongs to a certain tree *T*⊆*Fi*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] After the deletion of *e*, the tree *T* is broken to two smaller trees: *Tx* which contains the node *x* and *Ty* which contains the node *y*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] An edge of *Gi* is a replacement edge, if and only if it connects a node in *Tx* with a node in *Ty*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Suppose wlog that *Tx* is the smaller tree (i.e. contains at most half the nodes of *T*; we can tell the size of each subtree by an annotation added to the Euler trees).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] We first decrease the level of each edge of *Tx* by 1.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The level of each edge will be decreased at most lg *n* times.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Because with each decrease, it falls into a tree whose size is at most half the size of its tree in the previous level.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] So in each level *i*, the number of nodes in each connected component is at most 2*i*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Hence the level of an edge is always at least 0.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Each edge whose level is decreased, takes $O(\lg n)$ time to find (using the ET tree operations).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] In total, each inserted edge takes $O(\lg ^{2}n)$ time until it is deleted, so the amortized time for deletion is $O(\lg ^{2}n)$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The remaining part of delete also takes $O(\lg ^{2}n)$ time, since we have to delete the edge from at most $O(\lg n)$ levels, and deleting from each level takes $O(\lg n)$ (again using the ET operations).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] In total, the amortized time per update is $O(\lg ^{2}n)$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The time per query can be improved to $O(\lg n/\lg \lg n)$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] However, the worst-case time per update might be $O(n)$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The question of whether the worst-case time can be improved had been an open question, until it was solved in the affirmative by the Cutset structure.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Given a graph G(V, E) and a subset T⊆V, define **cutset(T)** as the set of edges that connect T with V\T.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The *cutset structure* is a data structure that, without keeping the entire graph in memory, can quickly find an edge in the cutset, if such an edge exists.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Start by giving a number to each vertex.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Suppose there are *n* vertices; then each vertex can be represented by a number with lg(*n*) bits.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Next, give a number to each edge, which is a concatenation of the numbers of its vertices - a number with 2 lg(*n*) bits.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] For each vertex *v*, calculate and keep xor(*v*), which is the xor of the numbers of all edges adjacent to it.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Now for each subset T⊆V, it is possible to calculate **xor(T)** = the xor of the values of all vertices in T.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Consider an edge *e* = *u*−*v* which is an internal edge of T (i.e. both *u* and *v* are in T).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The number of *e* is included twice in xor(T) - once for *u* and once for *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Since the xor of every number with itself is 0, *e* vanishes and does not affect xor(T).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Thus, xor(T) is actually the xor of all edges in cutset(T).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Our goal now is to handle this third option.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] First, create a sequence of lg(*n*) *levels* of the cutset structures, each of which contains about half the edges from the upper level (i.e., for each level, pick each edge from the upper level with probability 1/2).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If in the first level xor(T) returns an illegal value, meaning that cutset(T) has two or more edges, then there is a chance that in the next level, which contains fewer edges, xor(T) will return a legal value since cutset(T) will contain a single edge.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If xor(T) still returns an illegal value, continue to the next level, etc.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] It is possible to prove that the probability of success is at least 1/9.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Next, create a collection of *C* lg(*n*) independent versions of the level structure, where *C* is a constant.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] In each versions, do an independent random reduction of edges from level to level.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Try each query on each of the versions until one of them succeeds.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] By proper selection of *C* we can make the probability of failure arbitrarily close to 0.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] We can add a cutset structure to a dynamic connectivity structure.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The Insert and Delete operations on the cutset structure are done in exactly the same way: the edge inserted/deleted is XORed into both its endpoints.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] When an edge is deleted from the spanning forest used for the dynamic connectivity structure, the cutset structure is used to find a replacement edge.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] A single cutset structure requires only *O*(*n* lg *n*) memory - only a single number, with 2 lg *n* bits, for each of the *n* vertices.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] We don't have to keep the edges themselves.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] For dense graphs, this is much cheaper than keeping the entire graph in memory.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] We have to keep lg(*n*) versions, each of which contains lg(*n*) levels.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Hence, the total memory requirement is ⁠ $O(n\lg ^{3}n)$ ⁠.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] The query time is *O*(polylog(*n*)) in the worst case.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] This is in contrast to the Level structure, in which the query time is *O*(polylog(*n*)) amortized, but the worst-case time is *O*(*n*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If the order in which edges will be deleted is known ahead of time, then we can solve the dynamic connectivity problem in time $O(\log n)$ per query.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If we can maintain a maximum spanning forest where edges are ordered by their deletion time, we know that when we delete some edge that is in the forest, there is no possible edge that can replace it.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If there were some edge that connects the same two components the deleted edge does, then this other edge would have been part of the maximum spanning forest instead of the edge we deleted.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] This makes the delete operation trivial: we simply need to split the tree into its two parts if the edge to delete is part of our forest, or ignore the operation otherwise.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Adding an edge is slightly more complicated.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If we add an edge edge e from u to v, then if u and v are not connected, then this edge will be part of the maximum spanning forest.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If they are connected, we want to add u→v to our forest if it can improve our maximum spanning forest.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] To do this, we need to quickly check what edge has the smallest removal time on the path from u to v.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] If this edge's removal time comes after e's removal time, then e cannot improve our maximum spanning forest.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] Otherwise, the other edge should be deleted and replaced with e.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/dynamic-connectivity] This requires us to do the following operations: add an edge, cut an edge, and query the minimum edge on a path which can be done rather easily with a link-cut tree in log(n) per operation.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] The **Euler tour technique** (**ETT**), named after Leonhard Euler, is a method in graph theory for representing trees.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] The tree is viewed as a directed graph that contains two directed edges for each edge in the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] The tree can then be represented as a Eulerian circuit of the directed graph, known as the **Euler tour representation** (**ETR**) of the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] The ETT allows for efficient, parallel computation of solutions to common problems in algorithmic graph theory.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] It was introduced by Tarjan and Vishkin in 1984.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] The resulting list *succ* will be circular.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] The overall construction takes work *W*(*n*) = O(sort(*n*)) (the time it takes to sort *n* items in parallel) if the tree has *n* nodes, as in trees the number of edges is one less than the number of nodes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] If the tree has a root, we can split the circular list *succ* at that root.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] In that case, we can speak of *advance* and *retreat* edges: given a pair of nodes *u*,*v*, the first occurrence of either (*u*,*v*) or (*v*,*u*) in the ETR is called the *advance edge*, and the second occurrence is called the *retreat edge*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] This appeals to the intuition that the first time such an edge is traversed the distance to the root is increased, while the second time the distance decreases.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] Rerooting the tree can be done in constant time O(1) by splitting the circular list *succ* at the new root.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] Determine the level of each node: Do a prefix sum on the ETR, where every advance edge counts as 1, and every retreat edge counts as −1.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] Then the value at the advance edge (*u*,*v*) is the level of *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] Number of nodes in a subtree rooted at *v*: assume the parent of v is u, determine advance edge (*u*,*v*), and the retreat edge (*v*,*u*) in parallel, and then count the number of advance edges between (*u*,*v*) and (*v*,*u*) using prefix sum.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] The depth-first search index of a node *v*: count the number of advance edges up to and including (*u*,*v*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] Determine the lowest common ancestor of two nodes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] Henzinger and King suggest to represent a given tree by keeping its Euler tour in a balanced binary search tree, keyed by the index in the tour.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] So for example, the unbalanced tree in the example above, having 7 nodes, will be represented by a balanced binary tree with 14 nodes, one for each time each node appears on the tour.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] We can represent a forest (an acyclic graph) using a collection of ET trees - one ET tree for one forest tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] This representation allows us to quickly answer the question "what is the root of node v?" by just moving to the first node of the ET tree (since nodes in the ET tree are keyed by their location in the Euler tour, and the root is the first and last node in the tour).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] When the represented forest is updated (e.g. by connecting two trees to a single tree or by splitting a tree to two trees), the corresponding Euler-tour structure can be updated in time O(log(n)).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] Link/cut trees have similar performance guarantees.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/euler-tour-technique] While LC trees are good for maintaining aggregates on paths of a tree (making it a good choice data structure in network flow algorithms), ET trees are better at keeping aggregate information on subtrees.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The represented forest may consist of very deep trees, so if we represent the forest as a plain collection of parent pointer trees, it might take us a long time to find the root of a given node.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] However, if we represent each tree in the forest as a link/cut tree, we can find which tree an element belongs to in *O*(log(*n*)) amortized time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Moreover, we can quickly adjust the collection of link/cut trees to changes in the represented forest.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] In particular, we can adjust it to merge (link) and split (cut) in *O*(log(*n*)) amortized time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Link/cut trees divide each tree in the represented forest into vertex-disjoint paths, where each path is represented by an auxiliary data structure (often splay trees, though the original paper predates splay trees and thus uses biased binary search trees).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The nodes in the auxiliary data structure are ordered by their depth in the corresponding represented tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] In one variation, *Naive Partitioning*, the paths are determined by the most recently accessed paths and nodes, similar to Tango Trees.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] In *Partitioning by Size* paths are determined by the heaviest child (child with the most children) of the given node.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] This gives a more complicated structure, but reduces the cost of the operations from amortized O(log n) to worst case O(log n).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] It has uses in solving a variety of network flow problems and to jive data sets.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] In the original publication, Sleator and Tarjan referred to link/cut trees as "dynamic trees", or "dynamic dyno trees".
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We take a tree where each node has an arbitrary degree of unordered nodes and split it into paths.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] These paths are represented internally by auxiliary trees (here we will use splay trees), where the nodes from left to right represent the path from root to the last node on the path.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Nodes that are connected in the represented tree that are not on the same preferred path (and therefore not in the same auxiliary tree) are connected via a *path-parent pointer*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] This pointer is stored in the root of the auxiliary tree representing the path.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] When an access to a node *v* is made on the *represented tree*, the path that is taken becomes the **preferred path**.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The **preferred child** of a node is the last child that was on the access path, or null if the last access was to *v* or if no accesses were made to this particular branch of the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] A **preferred edge** is the edge that connects the **preferred child** to *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] In an alternate version, preferred paths are determined by the heaviest child.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The operations we are interested in are `FindRoot(Node v)`, `Cut(Node v)`, `Link(Node v, Node w)`, and `Path(Node v)`.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Every operation is implemented using the `Access(Node v)` subroutine.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] When we *access* a vertex *v*, the preferred path of the represented tree is changed to a path from the root *R* of the represented tree to the node *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] If a node on the access path previously had a preferred child *u*, and the path now goes to child *w*, the old *preferred edge* is deleted (changed to a *path-parent pointer*), and the new path now goes through *w*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] After performing an access to node *v*, it will no longer have any preferred children, and will be at the end of the path.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Since nodes in the auxiliary tree are keyed by depth, this means that any nodes to the right of *v* in the auxiliary tree must be disconnected.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] In a splay tree this is a relatively simple procedure; we splay at *v*, which brings *v* to the root of the auxiliary tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We then disconnect the right subtree of *v*, which is every node that came below it on the previous preferred path.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The root of the disconnected tree will have a path-parent pointer, which we point to *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We now walk up the represented tree to the root *R*, breaking and resetting the preferred path where necessary.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] To do this we follow the path-parent pointer from *v* (since *v* is now the root, we have direct access to the path-parent pointer).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] If the path that *v* is on already contains the root *R* (since the nodes are keyed by depth, it would be the left most node in the auxiliary tree), the path-parent pointer will be null, and we are done the access.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Otherwise we follow the pointer to some node on another path *w*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We want to break the old preferred path of *w* and reconnect it to the path *v* is on.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] To do this we splay at *w*, and disconnect its right subtree, setting its path-parent pointer to *w*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Since all nodes are keyed by depth, and every node in the path of *v* is deeper than every node in the path of *w* (since they are children of *w* in the represented tree), we simply connect the tree of *v* as the right child of *w*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We splay at *v* again, which, since *v* is a child of the root *w*, simply rotates *v* to root.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We repeat this entire process until the path-parent pointer of *v* is null, at which point it is on the same preferred path as the root of the represented tree *R*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] FindRoot refers to finding the root of the represented tree that contains the node *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Since the *access* subroutine puts *v* on the preferred path, we first execute an access.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Now the node *v* is on the same preferred path, and thus the same auxiliary tree as the root *R*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Since the auxiliary trees are keyed by depth, the root *R* will be the leftmost node of the auxiliary tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] So we simply choose the left child of *v* recursively until we can go no further, and this node is the root *R*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The root may be linearly deep (which is worst case for a splay tree), we therefore splay it so that the next access will be quick.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Here we would like to cut the represented tree at node *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] This puts all the elements lower than *v* in the represented tree as the right child of *v* in the auxiliary tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] All the elements now in the left subtree of *v* are the nodes higher than *v* in the represented tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We therefore disconnect the left child of *v* (which still maintains an attachment to the original represented tree through its path-parent pointer).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Now *v* is the root of a represented tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Accessing *v* breaks the preferred path below *v* as well, but that subtree maintains its connection to *v* through its path-parent pointer.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] If *v* is a tree root and *w* is a vertex in another tree, link the trees containing *v* and *w* by adding the edge(v, w), making *w* the parent of *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] To do this we access both *v* and *w* in their respective trees, and make *w* the left child of *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Since *v* is the root, and nodes are keyed by depth in the auxiliary tree, accessing *v* means that *v* will have no left child in the auxiliary tree (since as root it is the minimum depth).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Adding *w* as a left child effectively makes it the parent of *v* in the represented tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] For this operation we wish to do some aggregate function over all the nodes (or edges) on the path from root *R* to node *v* (such as "sum" or "min" or "max" or "increase", etc.).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] To do this we access *v*, which gives us an auxiliary tree with all the nodes on the path from root *R* to node *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The data structure can be augmented with data we wish to retrieve, such as min or max values, or the sum of the costs in the subtree, which can then be returned from a given path in constant time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Cut and link have *O*(1) cost, plus that of the access.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] FindRoot has an *O*(log *n*) amortized upper bound, plus the cost of the access.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The data structure can be augmented with additional information (such as the min or max valued node in its subtrees, or the sum), depending on the implementation.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Thus Path can return this information in constant time plus the access bound.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] So it remains to bound the *access* to find our running time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Access makes use of splaying, which we know has an *O*(log *n*) amortized upper bound.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] So the remaining analysis deals with the number of times we need to splay.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] This is equal to the number of preferred child changes (the number of edges changed in the preferred path) as we traverse up the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We bound *access* by using a technique called **Heavy-Light Decomposition**.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] This technique calls an edge heavy or light depending on the number of nodes in the subtree. ⁠ $Size(v)$ ⁠ represents the number of nodes in the subtree of *v* in the represented tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] An edge is called *heavy* if size(v) > 1⁄2 size(parent(v)).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Thus we can see that each node can have at most 1 *heavy* edge.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] An edge that is not a *heavy* edge is referred to as a *light* edge.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The *light-depth* refers to the number of light edges on a given path from root to vertex *v*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] *Light-depth* ≤ lg *n* because each time we traverse a light-edge we decrease the number of nodes by at least a factor of 2 (since it can have at most half the nodes of the parent).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] So a given edge in the represented tree can be any of four possibilities: *heavy-preferred*, *heavy-unpreferred*, *light-preferred* or *light-unpreferred*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] First we prove an $O(\log ^{2}n)$ upper bound.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The splay operation of the access gives us log *n*, so we need to bound the number of accesses to log *n* to prove the *O*(log 2 *n*) upper bound.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Every change of preferred edge results in a new preferred edge being formed.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] So we count the number of preferred edges formed.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Since there are at most log *n* edges that are light on any given path, there are at most log *n* light edges changing to preferred.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] The number of heavy edges becoming preferred can be ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ for any given operation, but it is ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠ amortized.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Over a series of executions we can have *n*-1 heavy edges become preferred (as there are at most *n*-1 heavy edges total in the represented tree), but from then on the number of heavy edges that become preferred is equal to the number of heavy edges that became unpreferred on a previous step.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] For every heavy edge that becomes unpreferred a light edge must become preferred.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We have seen already that the number of light edges that can become preferred is at most log *n*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] So the number of heavy edges that become preferred for *m* operations is ⁠ $m(\log n)+(n-1)$ ⁠.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Over enough operations (⁠ $m>n-1$ ⁠) this averages to ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] We have bound the number of preferred child changes at ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠, so if we can show that each preferred child change has cost O(1) amortized we can bound the *access* operation at ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] This is done using the potential method.
