[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Link/cut trees can be used to solve the dynamic connectivity problem for acyclic graphs.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Given two nodes x and y, they are connected if and only if FindRoot(x) = FindRoot(y).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] Another data structure that can be used for the same purpose is Euler tour tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/link-cut-tree] In solving the maximum flow problem, link/cut trees can be used to improve the running time of Dinic's algorithm from $O(V^{2}E)$ to $O(VE\log V)$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] A **splay tree** is a binary search tree with the additional property that recently accessed elements are quick to access again.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Like self-balancing binary search trees, a splay tree performs basic operations such as insertion, look-up and removal in O(log *n*) amortized time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] For random access patterns drawn from a non-uniform random distribution, their amortized time can be faster than logarithmic, proportional to the entropy of the access pattern.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] For many patterns of non-random operations, also, splay trees can take better than logarithmic time, without requiring prior knowledge of the pattern.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] According to the unproven dynamic optimality conjecture, their performance on all access patterns is within a constant factor of the best possible performance that could be achieved by any other self-adjusting binary search tree, even one selected to fit that pattern.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] The splay tree was invented by Daniel Sleator and Robert Tarjan in 1985.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] All normal operations on a binary search tree are combined with one basic operation, called *splaying*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Splaying the tree for a certain element rearranges the tree so that the element is placed at the root of the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] One way to do this with the basic search operation is to first perform a standard binary tree search for the element in question, and then use tree rotations in a specific fashion to bring the element to the top.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Alternatively, a top-down algorithm can combine the search and the tree reorganization into a single phase.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Good performance for a splay tree depends on the fact that it is self-optimizing, in that frequently accessed nodes will move nearer to the root where they can be accessed more quickly.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] The worst-case height—though unlikely—is O(*n*), with the average being O(log *n*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Having frequently-used nodes near the root is an advantage for many practical applications (also see locality of reference), and is particularly useful for implementing caches and garbage collection algorithms.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] The most significant disadvantage of splay trees is that the height of a splay tree can be linear.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] For example, this will be the case after accessing all *n* elements in non-decreasing order.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Since the height of a tree corresponds to the worst-case access time, this means that the actual cost of a single operation can be high.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] However the amortized access cost of this worst case is logarithmic, O(log *n*).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Also, the expected access cost can be reduced to O(log *n*) by using a randomized variant.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] The representation of splay trees can change even when they are accessed in a 'read-only' manner (i.e. by *find* operations).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] This complicates the use of such splay trees in a multi-threaded environment.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Specifically, extra management is needed if multiple threads are allowed to perform *find* operations concurrently.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] This also makes them unsuitable for general use in purely functional programming, although even there they can be used in limited ways to implement priority queues.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Finally, when the access pattern *is* random, the additional splaying overhead adds a significant constant factor to the cost compared to less-dynamic alternatives.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] When a node *x* is accessed, a splay operation is performed on *x* to move it to the root.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] A splay operation is a sequence of *splay steps*, each of which moves *x* closer to the root.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] By performing a splay operation on the node of interest after every access, the recently accessed nodes are kept near the root and the tree remains roughly balanced, so it provides the desired amortized time bounds.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] There are three types of splay steps, each of which has two symmetric variants: left- and right-handed.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] For the sake of brevity, only one of these two is shown for each type.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Given a tree and an element *x*, return two new trees: one containing all elements less than or equal to *x* and the other containing all elements greater than *x*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] As a result, the newly inserted node *x* becomes the root of the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] In this way, deletion is reduced to the problem of removing a node with 0 or 1 children.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Unlike a binary search tree, in a splay tree after deletion, we splay the parent of the removed node to the top of the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Splaying, as mentioned above, is performed during a second, bottom-up pass over the access path of a node.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] It is possible to record the access path during the first pass for use during the second, but that requires extra space during the access operation.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Another alternative is to keep a parent pointer in every node, which avoids the need for extra space during access operations but may reduce overall time efficiency because of the need to update those pointers.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Another method which can be used is based on the argument that the tree can be restructured during the way down the access path instead of making a second pass.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] This top-down splaying routine uses three sets of nodes – left tree, right tree and middle tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] The first two contain all items of original tree known to be less than or greater than current item respectively.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] The middle tree consists of the sub-tree rooted at the current node.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] These three sets are updated down the access path while keeping the splay operations in check.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Another method, semisplaying, modifies the zig-zig case to reduce the amount of restructuring done in all operations.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Below there is an implementation of splay trees in C++, which uses pointers to represent each node on the tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] This implementation is based on bottom-up splaying version and uses the second method of deletion on a splay tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/splay-tree] Also, unlike the above definition, this C++ version does *not* splay the tree on finds – it only splays on insertions and deletions, and the find operation, therefore, has linear time complexity.
