[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A **top tree** is a data structure based on a binary tree for unrooted dynamic trees that is used mainly for various path-related operations.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] It allows simple divide-and-conquer algorithms.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] It has since been augmented to maintain dynamically various properties of a tree such as diameter, center and median.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A vertex in a connected subtree is a *Boundary Vertex* if it is connected to a vertex outside the subtree by an edge.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Up to a pair of vertices in the top tree $\Re$ can be called as External Boundary Vertices, they can be thought of as Boundary Vertices of the cluster which represents the entire top tree.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A *cluster* is a connected subtree with at most two Boundary Vertices.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The set of Boundary Vertices of a given cluster C is denoted as $\partial {C}.$ With each cluster C the user may associate some meta information $I({\mathcal {C}}),$ and give methods to maintain it under the various internal operations.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] If $\pi ({\mathcal {C}})$ contains at least one edge then C is called a *Path Cluster*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] If $\pi ({\mathcal {C}})$ does not contain any edge i.e.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] C has only one Boundary Vertex then C is called a *Leaf Cluster*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A Cluster containing a single edge is called an *Edge Cluster*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A Leaf in the original Cluster is represented by a Cluster with just a single Boundary Vertex and is called a *Leaf Edge Cluster*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Edge Clusters with two Boundary Nodes are called *Path Edge Cluster*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A node in ${\mathcal {C}}\setminus \partial {C}$ is called an *Internal Node* of C.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Two Clusters A and B are *Mergeable* if ${\mathcal {A}}\cap {\mathcal {B}}$ is a singleton set (they have exactly one node in common) and ${\mathcal {A}}\cup {\mathcal {B}}$ is a Cluster.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The basic idea is to maintain a balanced Binary tree $\Re$ of logarithmic height in the number of nodes in the original tree T( i.e. in ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ time); the **top tree** essentially represents the recursive subdivision of the original tree T into clusters.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] In general the tree T may have weight on its edges.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] There is a one-to-one correspondence with the edges of the original tree T and the leaf nodes of the top tree $\Re$ and each internal node of $\Re$ represents a cluster that is formed due to the union of the clusters that are its children.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The top tree data structure can be initialized in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A tree with a single vertex has an empty top tree, and one with just an edge is just a single node.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] These trees are freely augmentable allowing the user a wide variety of flexibility and productivity without going into the details of the internal workings of the data structure, something which is also referred to as the *Black Box*.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The following three are the user allowable Forest Updates.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The Forest updates are all carried out by a sequence of at most ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ Internal Operations, the sequence of which is computed in further ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ time.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] It may happen that during a tree update, a leaf cluster may change to a path cluster and the converse.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Updates to top tree are done exclusively by these internal operations.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The $I({\mathcal {C}})$ is updated by calling a user defined function associated with each internal operation.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Split is usually implemented using $\mathrm {Clean} ({\mathcal {C}})$ method which calls user method for updates of $I({\mathcal {A}})$ and $I({\mathcal {B}})$ using $I({\mathcal {C}})$ and updates $I({\mathcal {C}})$ such that it's known there is no pending update needed in its children.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Then the C is discarded without calling user defined functions.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] **Clean** is often required for queries without need to **Split**.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] If Split does not use Clean subroutine, and Clean is required, its effect could be achieved with overhead by combining **Merge** and **Split**.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The next two functions are analogous to the above two and are used for base clusters.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] User can define **Choose $({\mathcal {C}}){:}$** operation which for a root (nonleaf) cluster selects one of its child clusters.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The top tree blackbox provides **Search $({\mathcal {C}}){:}$** routine, which organizes **Choose** queries and reorganization of the top tree (using the Internal operations) such that it locates the only edge in intersection of all selected clusters.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Sometimes the search should be limited to a path.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] There is a variant of nonlocal search for such purposes.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] If there are two external boundary vertices in the root cluster C, the edge is searched only on the path $\pi ({\mathcal {C}})$ .
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] It is sufficient to do following modification: If only one of root cluster children is path cluster, it is selected by default without calling the **Choose** operation.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Finding i-th edge on longer path from v to w could be done by **C=Expose({v,w})** followed by **Search(C)** with appropriate **Choose**.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] To implement the **Choose** we use global variable representing v and global variable representing i.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Choose selects the cluster A with $v\in \partial {A}$ iff length of $\pi ({\mathcal {A}})$ is at least i.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] To support the operation the length must be maintained in the I.
