[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A number of interesting applications originally implemented by other methods have been easily implemented using the top tree's interface.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Top trees have been implemented in a variety of ways, some of them include implementation using a *Multilevel Partition* (Top-trees and dynamic graph algorithms Jacob Holm and Kristian de Lichtenberg.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Technical Report), and even by using Sleator-Tarjan s-t trees (typically with amortized time bounds), Frederickson's Topology Trees (with worst case time bounds) (Alstrup et al.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Maintaining Information in Fully Dynamic Trees with Top Trees).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Amortized implementations are more simple, and with small multiplicative factors in time complexity.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] On the contrary the worst case implementations allow speeding up queries by switching off unneeded info updates during the query (implemented by persistence techniques).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] After the query is answered the original state of the top tree is used and the query version is discarded.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Any partitioning of clusters of a tree T can be represented by a Cluster Partition Tree CPT $({\mathcal {T}}),$ by replacing each cluster in the tree T by an edge.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] If we use a strategy P for partitioning T then the CPT would be CPTP ${\mathcal {T}}.$ This is done recursively till only one edge remains.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] We would notice that all the nodes of the corresponding top tree $\Re$ are uniquely mapped into the edges of this multilevel partition.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] There may be some edges in the multilevel partition that do not correspond to any node in the top tree, these are the edges which represent only a single child in the level below it, i.e. a simple cluster.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] A partitioning strategy is important while we partition the Tree T into clusters.
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] Only a careful strategy ensures that we end up in an ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ height Multilevel Partition ( and therefore the top tree).
[src:dynamic-tree-structure/top-tree] The above partitioning strategy ensures the maintenance of the top tree in ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ time.
